# JsonSettings classes

Settings persistence uses `nucs.JsonSettings` + `nucs.JsonSettings.Autosave`. The autosave proxy intercepts property setters at runtime via Castle DynamicProxy, so:

## All settable properties MUST be `virtual`

```csharp
public class LyricsSettings : JsonSettings
{
    public override string FileName { get; set; }

    public virtual double FontSize { get; set; } = 25;   // virtual = autosaved
    public virtual bool IsItalic { get; set; }
}
```

A non-virtual property silently breaks autosave for that field. When adding new properties to existing settings types, always mark them `virtual`.

## Loading and registration

Settings are loaded once in `App.xaml.cs > LoadSettings<T>` and registered as singletons via `containerRegistry.RegisterInstance(...)`. To add a new settings type:

1. Create `XxxSettings : JsonSettings` (or `XxxProviderSettings` for provider-scoped) with `override string FileName { get; set; }`.
2. Add a `RegisterInstance(LoadSettings<XxxSettings>("xxx.json"))` line in `RegisterTypes`.
3. Inject `XxxSettings` (constructor parameter) wherever you need it.

`LoadSettings<T>` already handles corrupt files (backs up to `.bak`, deletes original, reloads defaults). Don't reimplement that.

## Backward compatibility

For renamed/retyped fields, keep a private setter under the old JSON name:

```csharp
public virtual double TimeOffsetSeconds { get; set; } = 0.5;

[JsonProperty(nameof(TimeOffsetMilliseconds))]
private double TimeOffsetMilliseconds { set => TimeOffsetSeconds = value / 1000.0; }
```

## After-load hooks

Use `AfterLoad += ...` in the constructor to merge defaults into collections (see `Settings.OnAfterLoad` adding default provider entries via `Union`). Don't do this in property initializers - the file isn't loaded yet.

## Serializer settings

`JsonSettings.SerializationSettings` is configured globally in `App.RegisterTypes` (StringEnumConverter, `MissingMemberHandling.Ignore`). Don't override it per-class.
